3. CREATE app/services/mrr_validator.py

   The Excel validator + resolver. Pure functions, no DB writes.

   Required columns in the Excel (exact, case-insensitive):
   - Project Number
   - Requisition Type
   - Need By Date
   - Description
   - Comments
   - Item Name
   - Requested Quantity
   - Return Date

   Allowed REQUISITIONTYPE values: "RETURNABLE", "NONRETURNABLE"
   (case-insensitive, uppercase the value before validation).

   Date formats accepted: pandas-parseable date strings. Treat as
   DATE (no time component) for Need By Date and Return Date.

   Validation rules:

   R1. Required columns all present. Missing any → reject.
   R2. At least one data row (excluding header row).
   R3. Header fields (cols 1-5) identical across all rows.
       Different value on any row → reject with "Header field X
       must be the same on all rows; found '...' and '...'."
   R4. Requisition Type ∈ {"RETURNABLE", "NONRETURNABLE"}.
   R5. Need By Date parseable as date, in future (>= today).
   R6. If Requisition Type == "RETURNABLE":
       - Return Date is required on every row.
       - Return Date parseable as date.
       - Return Date >= Need By Date (return after need-by).
       Else (NONRETURNABLE):
       - Return Date is ignored (logged but not validated).
   R7. Item Name non-empty string on every row.
   R8. Requested Quantity is a positive integer or decimal > 0.

   Resolution rules (run AFTER all validation passes):

   Resolution 1 — Project: get_project_by_number(project_number) →
   if None, error "Project number 'XYZ' not found."
   Else: capture project_id, project description, warehouse_id.

   Resolution 2 — Project Phase: get_project_phase(project_id) →
   if None, error "No phase found for project 'XYZ'."
   Else: capture phase_id, phase_name.

   Resolution 3 — Department: get_department_id(user_dept) where
   user_dept comes from CurrentUser. If None, error "Department
   '<user_dept>' not found in SCM departments."

   Resolution 4 — Per line item:
   a. get_item_id_by_name(item_name) → if None, error "Item '<name>'
      not found." Add to errors, continue to next item.
   b. get_item_full_details(item_id) → if None, error "Item details
      for '<name>' not retrievable." Continue.
   c. uom_id from full_details.unitofmeasureid.
   d. get_uom_name(uom_id) — for display only; if None, fallback "UNKNOWN".
   e. get_latest_item_revision(item_id) → if None, defaults to 0.
   f. get_item_lpp(item_id, warehouse_id=1) → if None, lpp_rate = 0.
      If lpp_rate is 0, add a warning (not blocking) "LPP unavailable
      for '<name>'; cost will be calculated as 0."
   g. get_item_availability(item_id) — for display only; if None,
      onhand_quantity = "unknown".
   h. item_cost = lpp_rate × requested_quantity.

   After all items resolved, compute:
   - total_cost = SUM(item_cost) across all items.

   Compute MRR number:
   from app.services.mrr_helpers import next_mrr_number
   (next_seq, mrr_no) = next_mrr_number()

   Return structure:

   If any errors:
     {
       "valid": False,
       "errors": ["...", "..."],
       "warnings": []
     }

   If valid:
     {
       "valid": True,
       "errors": [],
       "warnings": ["LPP unavailable for ...", ...],
       "summary_for_user": "<friendly text representation>",
       "header": {
           "mrr_no": "DPE/MRR/12/26-27",
           "next_seq": 12,
           "warehouse_id": 1,
           "requisition_type": "RETURNABLE",
           "requestor_id": "<emp_no>",
           "department_id": 6,
           "department_name": "SDG",
           "need_by_date": "2026-11-28",
           "status": "ENTERED",
           "project_id": 12001,
           "project_number": "YEB1021",
           "project_description": "cPCI system for Mark III",
           "project_phase_id": 12001,
           "phase_name": "PRODUCTION",
           "req_transaction_type": "MATERIAL REQUISITION",
           "supplier_id": 0,
           "supplier_site_id": 0,
           "description": "<user description>",
           "comments": "<user comments>",
           "total_cost": 5550.0
       },
       "lines": [
           {
               "item_id": 1001,
               "item_name": "DP-RM-CAB-03890",
               "item_revision_id": 19354,
               "uom_id": 7,
               "uom_name": "NUMBERS",
               "requisition_qty": 5.0,
               "lpp_rate": 150.0,
               "item_cost": 750.0,
               "available_quantity": 12,
               "return_date": "2026-12-15"  # None if NONRETURNABLE
           },
           ...
       ]
     }

   The summary_for_user field is a multi-line string formatted for
   chat display. Format:

   "**Material Requisition — Review Before Submit**\n\n"
   "MRR Number: {mrr_no}\n"
   "Requestor: emp {requestor_id}\n"
   "Department: {department_name}\n"
   "Project: {project_number} — {project_description}\n"
   "Phase: {phase_name}\n"
   "Requisition Type: {requisition_type}\n"
   "Need by: {need_by_date}\n"
   "Description: {description}\n"
   "Comments: {comments}\n\n"
   "**Line Items:**\n"
   For each line:
   "  {n}. {item_name} — UOM: {uom_name}\n"
   "     Qty: {requisition_qty} | Available: {available_quantity}\n"
   "     Unit Cost (LPP): ₹{lpp_rate:.2f} | Subtotal: ₹{item_cost:.2f}\n"
   (If returnable) "     Return by: {return_date}\n"
   "\n"
   "**Total Cost: ₹{total_cost:,.2f}**\n"

   Public function signature:

   def validate_and_resolve_mrr_excel(
       excel_data: list[dict],   # rows as dicts from _parse_excel
       current_user: CurrentUser
   ) -> dict:
       """
       Validates and resolves an MRR Excel upload.

       Args:
           excel_data: list of row dicts (from chat_controller._parse_excel
                       output's "data" field).
           current_user: the authenticated user.

       Returns:
           Validation result dict (see structure above).
       """

   Use the existing helper functions from:
   - app.services.mariadb_queries (resolver helpers)
   - app.services.mrr_helpers (next_mrr_number, etc.)
   - app.models.dto_schemas (CurrentUser)

   Validation should accumulate ALL errors before returning, not
   short-circuit on first error. User wants to see all problems at
   once, not fix one at a time.

   But resolution short-circuits per item — if Item Name doesn't
   resolve to an ITEMID, we don't proceed with its UOM/revision/LPP
   resolution. Skip that item, accumulate the error, continue with
   the next item.

   No need to log to console — let exceptions propagate naturally
   to whoever calls the function.

